  <a href="#1" id="1">
   POLYP IN DALLAS
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   Retired Sen. John Tower, the defense secretary-designate, underwent surgery on Jan. 4, 1989 to remove a colon polyp, a hospital spokesman said.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Tower, 63, a U.S. senator from Texas for 24 years, was admitted to Baylor University Medical Center on Jan. 3, 1989 after undergoing a colonscopy examination the week of Dec. 29, 1989 that revealed the polyp, Habgood said.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   Further explanation of the first polyp removal would have to come from Tower's surgeon, who was unavailable for comment on Jan. 4, 1989 night, the spokesman said.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   "Senator Tower is resting comfortably and is listed in fair condition," hospital spokesman Steve Habgood said on Jan. 4, 1989 night.
  </a>
